00:01:53.110 --> 00:01:57.970
I thank Gail for inviting me to
be part of this event which is

00:01:57.970 --> 00:02:01.170
in a way a commemoration
of Kristallnacht

00:02:01.170 --> 00:02:06.270
which happened November
9th and 10, 1938.

00:02:06.270 --> 00:02:09.010
I just want to say a
few words about that.

00:02:09.010 --> 00:02:13.190
Kristallnacht is not a word that
Holocaust survivors like to use

00:02:13.190 --> 00:02:17.390
for this event because it has
a little positive connotation.

00:02:17.390 --> 00:02:19.490
You know, Kristall is beautiful.

00:02:19.490 --> 00:02:24.240
So they prefer to call it
the night of broken glass.

00:02:24.240 --> 00:02:29.900
The I guess excuse for that
evening, for that night,

00:02:29.900 --> 00:02:33.400
was the fact that a young man by
the name of Herschel Grynszpan,

00:02:33.400 --> 00:02:41.080
who was 17 years old, was very,
very frustrated because in 1938,

00:02:41.080 --> 00:02:46.790
towards the end of 1938, many
German Jewish people who were

00:02:46.790 --> 00:02:51.800
of Polish descent were
suddenly sent back to Poland.

00:02:51.800 --> 00:02:58.130
Some of these people were in
Germany from 1900 and even before.

00:02:58.130 --> 00:03:02.390
Herschel Grynszpan's
parents were there from 1911.

00:03:02.390 --> 00:03:09.600
And he was so upset that they were
sent to Zbaszyn which was a town

00:03:09.600 --> 00:03:12.270 position:56%
on the border of Poland and Germany.

00:03:12.270 --> 00:03:15.420
So they were in a camp in
Poland and had nowhere to go.

00:03:15.420 --> 00:03:18.360
They had lost all their
contacts in Poland,

00:03:18.360 --> 00:03:20.300
and so were many other people.

00:03:20.300 --> 00:03:23.690
So he went to the German
Embassy in Paris,

00:03:23.690 --> 00:03:28.120
and was very frustrated
talking to Ernst vom Rath

00:03:28.120 --> 00:03:32.240
who was an employee
at the embassy there.

00:03:32.240 --> 00:03:36.120
And finally he just took
out his gun and shot him.

00:03:36.120 --> 00:03:41.930 position:56%
And that was the excuse for
everything that happened that night.

00:03:41.930 --> 00:03:48.360
It was encouraged by two well
known Nazis, Hydriff [phonetic]

00:03:48.360 --> 00:03:53.900
and Gerbals [phonetic], and that
evening 267 synagogues in Germany,

00:03:53.900 --> 00:03:57.600
Austria and in the
Protectorate were burned

00:03:57.600 --> 00:04:04.730
down as were 7,500 Jewish
businesses, many Jewish cemeteries,

00:04:04.730 --> 00:04:07.550
Jewish schools and Jewish homes.

00:04:07.550 --> 00:04:12.630
So it was really the beginning of
what we now call the Holocaust.

00:04:12.630 --> 00:04:15.970
And I think this presentation
is very, very appropriate

00:04:15.970 --> 00:04:20.490
to remember that horrendous day.

00:04:20.490 --> 00:04:24.990
So I have to admit that I'm not
an objective presenter here.

00:04:24.990 --> 00:04:30.950
I have known the authors, Tony,
for a very, very long time

00:04:30.950 --> 00:04:34.300
and his works, his
books for a long time.

00:04:34.300 --> 00:04:38.780
I know he's an excellent
author and so is this book.

00:04:38.780 --> 00:04:45.220 position:56%
I like to always remember the moment
when I saw President Clinton going

00:04:45.220 --> 00:04:49.280
on vacation to Martha's Vineyard
with Tony's book on the Burning

00:04:49.280 --> 00:04:52.500
of Washington in his hand
so the world could see it.

00:04:52.500 --> 00:04:55.970
And that was fantastic publicity.

00:04:55.970 --> 00:04:58.740
And, of course, his book
on the assassination

00:04:58.740 --> 00:05:02.160
of President Lincoln
is also very famous

00:05:02.160 --> 00:05:05.810
as are his other 10 or 11 books.

00:05:05.810 --> 00:05:08.870
And so the years that I've
known him I won't even tell you

00:05:08.870 --> 00:05:10.230
because it's so many.

00:05:10.230 --> 00:05:14.990
I haven't known Nancy as many
years, but I feel very close to her

00:05:14.990 --> 00:05:20.710
because we've worked both
with Tony and with Nancy

00:05:20.710 --> 00:05:24.090
on their research actually
from the very beginning

00:05:24.090 --> 00:05:28.740
when they just started thinking
about writing their books.

00:05:28.740 --> 00:05:33.350
I think Tony was not sure exactly
what he wanted to do immediately,

00:05:33.350 --> 00:05:35.240
and I'm sure you'll hear
that a little later.

00:05:35.240 --> 00:05:40.460 position:56%
But he knew that it was time for him
to write a book on the Holocaust.

00:05:40.460 --> 00:05:47.090
And Nancy was fortunate I think, as
was Joe Rubinstein that they met,

00:05:47.090 --> 00:05:52.240
and eventually the book has been
written, and it is here available

00:05:52.240 --> 00:05:55.930
and of information to
everyone around the world.

00:05:55.930 --> 00:05:58.190
And I know Nancy is in
contact with people all

00:05:58.190 --> 00:06:00.610
over the world because of the book.

00:06:00.610 --> 00:06:05.680
So our work together was at the
Holocaust Museum where I have been

00:06:05.680 --> 00:06:12.370
for 16 years in working in
reference, now more specifically

00:06:12.370 --> 00:06:14.380
on the fate of individuals.

00:06:14.380 --> 00:06:18.840
And, therefore, Joe
Rubinstein's store was exactly

00:06:18.840 --> 00:06:21.200
in my area of research.

00:06:21.200 --> 00:06:26.550
And we did find all kinds of
information on him during the war,

00:06:26.550 --> 00:06:29.890
how he moved from camp
to camp, and how he came

00:06:29.890 --> 00:06:32.310
to the United States and so forth.

00:06:32.310 --> 00:06:35.790
And when Tony eventually
decided that he wanted to look

00:06:35.790 --> 00:06:42.240
into oral histories, we worked
together to see which ones

00:06:42.240 --> 00:06:44.480
and how he would access them.

00:06:44.480 --> 00:06:48.940
The museum has an enormous
resource for Holocaust studies.

00:06:48.940 --> 00:06:52.160
Not only does the museum
have its own Center

00:06:52.160 --> 00:06:55.560
for Advanced Holocaust Studies
where there are scholars,

00:06:55.560 --> 00:07:01.670
but there are also interns and
fellows a the museum all the time

00:07:01.670 --> 00:07:03.760
from all around the world.

00:07:03.760 --> 00:07:06.970
And they work on so
many different areas.

00:07:06.970 --> 00:07:11.320
We know that the Holocaust
is the most documented event

00:07:11.320 --> 00:07:13.720
in human history.

00:07:13.720 --> 00:07:16.620
So the documentation is enormous.

00:07:16.620 --> 00:07:19.960
We have in the library
over 100,000 books.

00:07:19.960 --> 00:07:24.100
These books are in every
language that you can imagine.

00:07:24.100 --> 00:07:26.700
Any book that's been
written on any aspect

00:07:26.700 --> 00:07:29.990
of the Holocaust the
museum tries to get.

00:07:29.990 --> 00:07:34.180
And so there are books in Chinese
and in Japanese and languages

00:07:34.180 --> 00:07:36.550
that you would not imagine.

00:07:36.550 --> 00:07:41.250
And there are 100 million
pages of archival information.

00:07:41.250 --> 00:07:45.740
The museum has been collecting
this for over 21 years.

00:07:45.740 --> 00:07:47.570
That's how long the
museum has been open.

00:07:47.570 --> 00:07:52.500 position:56%
But many years before that when it
was just an idea information started

00:07:52.500 --> 00:07:53.830
to be collected.

00:07:53.830 --> 00:07:58.010
So that, and then there
are 100,000 photographs

00:07:58.010 --> 00:08:01.010
and 10,000 or more interviews.

00:08:01.010 --> 00:08:04.650
So for all these scholars when they
come to research they need help

00:08:04.650 --> 00:08:08.340
to navigate through this
wealth of information.

00:08:08.340 --> 00:08:13.540
And that's what we do when we help
them in doing the reference work.

00:08:13.540 --> 00:08:16.800
A lot of the information is
available on the website.

00:08:16.800 --> 00:08:20.620
But, of course, much has
not been digitized yet.

00:08:20.620 --> 00:08:26.170
It is I think the idea that
eventually this will happen,

00:08:26.170 --> 00:08:29.830
but it will be a long time
because those of you who have been

00:08:29.830 --> 00:08:34.050
to the museum to the permanent
exhibit, everything that's there is

00:08:34.050 --> 00:08:37.030
about five percent of
what the museum has.

00:08:37.030 --> 00:08:43.550
The rest, the 95 percent is
kept in a state of the art area

00:08:43.550 --> 00:08:47.330
where temperature, pressure
and humidity are very,

00:08:47.330 --> 00:08:48.770
very carefully controlled.

00:08:48.770 --> 00:08:54.090
And we are building a new
structure just for that.

00:08:54.090 --> 00:08:58.030
So my interaction with these two
authors has been very interesting.

00:08:58.030 --> 00:09:01.530
And to see how the process evolved

00:09:01.530 --> 00:09:05.320
so that there is a book
is always amazing to me.

00:09:05.320 --> 00:09:09.620
Because sometimes it's an idea in
someone's mind, and it takes five

00:09:09.620 --> 00:09:12.890
or sometimes even ten
years to see the product

00:09:12.890 --> 00:09:15.400
and be able to actually read it.

00:09:15.400 --> 00:09:21.130 position:56%
I think that both Nancy and Tony
had in mind the words of Elie Wiesel

00:09:21.130 --> 00:09:26.840 position:56%
who warned that only those who were
there can write about the Holocaust.

00:09:26.840 --> 00:09:31.200
And that's why I think they went
to the horse's mouth, so to speak,

00:09:31.200 --> 00:09:34.140
to those survivors
who were interviewed

00:09:34.140 --> 00:09:37.290
or the survivor was alive.

00:09:37.290 --> 00:09:40.610
And I think they're
also trying to make sure

00:09:40.610 --> 00:09:44.360
that these memories are
there for us to remember.

00:09:44.360 --> 00:09:46.850
Because Elie Wiesel also said

00:09:46.850 --> 00:09:50.960
that if we forget we'll cause
them to have a second death.

00:09:50.960 --> 00:09:53.730
And unfortunately that is true.

00:09:53.730 --> 00:09:56.550
The only thing that we
have really from those

00:09:56.550 --> 00:10:02.540 position:56%
who were there are the memoirs and
oral histories of those who survive.

00:10:02.540 --> 00:10:05.980
So they used raw testimonies,

00:10:05.980 --> 00:10:10.460
and for Our Crime Was
Being Jewish Tony combed

00:10:10.460 --> 00:10:15.660
through the museum's oral history
interviews and listened to,

00:10:15.660 --> 00:10:20.530
as you heard, 358 of them
and pulled out of them some

00:10:20.530 --> 00:10:26.640
of the most powerful and
poignant testimonies.

00:10:26.640 --> 00:10:31.850
Symbolically that book is like
the chaos of the Holocaust.

00:10:31.850 --> 00:10:33.670
There's no arrangement.

00:10:33.670 --> 00:10:39.470
It's not arranged by geographical
place or in any other way,

00:10:39.470 --> 00:10:42.970
not chronologically or by subject.

00:10:42.970 --> 00:10:46.440
And there's no index because
I think the author felt

00:10:46.440 --> 00:10:51.170
that if he indexed the
358 names one would think

00:10:51.170 --> 00:10:52.760
that these were all of them.

00:10:52.760 --> 00:10:55.140
But all the others,
especially the victims,

00:10:55.140 --> 00:10:57.610
would not have been on the list.

00:10:57.610 --> 00:11:02.870
And those evil acts that were
perpetrated by the Nazis are

00:11:02.870 --> 00:11:07.740
so coldly described in the
passages that Tony pulled

00:11:07.740 --> 00:11:12.690
out that one is left holding
your breath in disbelief.

00:11:12.690 --> 00:11:16.650
I think this book will be a very
useful resource for teachers

00:11:16.650 --> 00:11:20.230
of all age because the
information is right there.

00:11:20.230 --> 00:11:21.910
And they will not have to comb

00:11:21.910 --> 00:11:25.580
through all these interviews
as Tony had to.

00:11:25.580 --> 00:11:31.320
And it is really excellent
documentation of those crimes.

00:11:31.320 --> 00:11:35.320
Nancy Geise, on the other
hand, focused on one person.

00:11:35.320 --> 00:11:38.000 position:56%
And she interviewed him masterfully.

00:11:38.000 --> 00:11:40.380
He was very reluctant at first.

00:11:40.380 --> 00:11:45.000
Actually, you will hear from
Nancy, did not want to talk.

00:11:45.000 --> 00:11:48.670
I think it just was too
painful for him to remember.

00:11:48.670 --> 00:11:55.140
But after several years
possibly because of his guilt

00:11:55.140 --> 00:11:59.780
that he was the only one that
survived he felt that he needed

00:11:59.780 --> 00:12:05.200
to talk to be the one who would
record what happened to his family,

00:12:05.200 --> 00:12:07.440
too, everyone in his family.

00:12:07.440 --> 00:12:11.690
His fortune was that he was a
very positive thinking person.

00:12:11.690 --> 00:12:15.860
Because even in the total
darkness of the war he was able

00:12:15.860 --> 00:12:18.540
to see some rays of light.

00:12:18.540 --> 00:12:22.460
And he was able to make a new and
wonderful life in the United States

00:12:22.460 --> 00:12:24.450
for himself and his family.

00:12:24.450 --> 00:12:27.360
And you will hear more
about it very soon.

00:12:27.360 --> 00:12:29.300
Nancy's book is very readable.

00:12:29.300 --> 00:12:33.760
She divided it into sections,
and they are very accessible.

00:12:33.760 --> 00:12:37.420
She provides historical
background to events describe

00:12:37.420 --> 00:12:41.560
by Auschwitz prisoner #34201.

00:12:41.560 --> 00:12:45.970
And she included maps, documents,
photographs and a time line

00:12:45.970 --> 00:12:49.030
so that one could read it and
really get the background,

00:12:49.030 --> 00:12:50.640
not just what happened to Joe

00:12:50.640 --> 00:12:54.170
but what was happening
during the war at that time.

00:12:54.170 --> 00:12:56.900
The reviews of both books
have been excellent,

00:12:56.900 --> 00:12:58.880
and you might hear more about that.

00:12:58.880 --> 00:13:03.570
And I think we're really very
fortunate to have Anthony Pitch

00:13:03.570 --> 00:13:09.230
and Nancy Geise talk about the
issues of writing the Holocaust.

00:13:09.230 --> 00:13:14.090
So I invite Tony to come up here,
and I have some questions for you

00:13:14.090 --> 00:13:18.430
so that we will hear how this
process of writing went on.

00:13:18.430 --> 00:13:28.580
My first question is what led
you to decide after all the books

00:13:28.580 --> 00:13:33.980
that you wrote that you needed to
write a book about the Holocaust?

00:13:33.980 --> 00:13:35.290
&gt;&gt; Anthony Pitch: Good question.

00:13:35.290 --> 00:13:38.550
Look, I must at the
beginning apologize.

00:13:38.550 --> 00:13:44.530
I had a stroke, and my short-term
memory is not what it used to be.

00:13:44.530 --> 00:13:48.270
In fact, I recently forgot
what I was talking about.

00:13:48.270 --> 00:13:51.360
I hope it doesn't happen today.

00:13:51.360 --> 00:13:53.370
Why did I choose the Holocaust?

00:13:53.370 --> 00:13:57.250
I had always been attracted
by subjects

00:13:57.250 --> 00:14:00.960
that were epic, true and sad.

00:14:00.960 --> 00:14:04.790
I don't know why, but
that's a fact of life.

00:14:04.790 --> 00:14:08.440
And that's why I wrote about
Vietnam, [inaudible] held prisoner,

00:14:08.440 --> 00:14:13.210
the burning of the White House
and the capital by the British,

00:14:13.210 --> 00:14:14.680
the Lincoln assassination.

00:14:14.680 --> 00:14:16.890
They all fit that mold.

00:14:16.890 --> 00:14:23.240
And then I thought, well, the
Holocaust is in that mold also.

00:14:23.240 --> 00:14:27.390
And probably it was my daughter
said to me don't touch it.

00:14:27.390 --> 00:14:31.000
It's been overdone, it's
been written by everybody.

00:14:31.000 --> 00:14:32.720
There's nothing new you can say.

00:14:32.720 --> 00:14:36.850
And I accepted that,
and I put it aside.

00:14:36.850 --> 00:14:40.220
And then one day I was
looking at at YouTube,

00:14:40.220 --> 00:14:44.500
and I saw Dieudonne M'bala M'bala.

00:14:44.500 --> 00:14:48.350
He is a Frenchman whose
father was Cameroonian

00:14:48.350 --> 00:14:49.730
and his mother was French.

00:14:49.730 --> 00:14:51.710
He lives in France.

00:14:51.710 --> 00:14:54.500
And this is the ranking anti-semite

00:14:54.500 --> 00:14:58.220
in Europe today, Dieudonne
M'Bala M'Bala.

00:14:58.220 --> 00:15:03.370
He has an enormous following
and he ridicules the Holocaust.

00:15:03.370 --> 00:15:09.490
He has Shoananas, shoa you know
and ananas is pineapple in French.

00:15:09.490 --> 00:15:13.520 position:56%
And he plays with the pineapple
while he's ridiculing the Holocaust.

00:15:13.520 --> 00:15:17.470
And he's making a fortune,
and he's getting followers

00:15:17.470 --> 00:15:19.430
like nobody's business.

00:15:19.430 --> 00:15:24.330
It so infuriated me that
I had to reply to him.

00:15:24.330 --> 00:15:27.600
And the best method I could do was

00:15:27.600 --> 00:15:31.340
by getting the Holocaust
survivors themselves

00:15:31.340 --> 00:15:34.820
to tell him what they went
through, what they endured.

00:15:34.820 --> 00:15:38.070
And that's why I chose this book.

00:15:38.070 --> 00:15:40.810 position:56%
And I wrote the preface, that's all.

00:15:40.810 --> 00:15:43.060
I let them speak for themselves.

00:15:43.060 --> 00:15:48.990
I excerpted brief amounts that
they could describe the range

00:15:48.990 --> 00:15:50.630
of atrocities.

00:15:50.630 --> 00:15:55.980
And it's one of those things that
all Holocaust survivors have,

00:15:55.980 --> 00:16:01.320
the urge to record it for
a world naive to believe

00:16:01.320 --> 00:16:03.670
that it appears again and again.

00:16:03.670 --> 00:16:05.750
And these are their
statements, not mine.

00:16:05.750 --> 00:16:08.200
It's their wisdom.

00:16:08.200 --> 00:16:11.370
&gt;&gt; Michlean Amir: So
my next question is,

00:16:11.370 --> 00:16:14.120
although you partially answered it,

00:16:14.120 --> 00:16:18.480 position:56%
but how was writing this book
different from writing about Lincoln

00:16:18.480 --> 00:16:20.800
or about the White House?

00:16:20.800 --> 00:16:22.880
Writing it how was that different?

00:16:22.880 --> 00:16:25.730
&gt;&gt; Anthony Pitch: It's
different in this respect.

00:16:25.730 --> 00:16:30.010
I had to insert myself
into my other books.

00:16:30.010 --> 00:16:33.950
And I did research from
Harvard right down to Alabama.

00:16:33.950 --> 00:16:35.890
Any document I could get hold of.

00:16:35.890 --> 00:16:38.930
There are state historical
societies all over the place.

00:16:38.930 --> 00:16:41.290
There's no end to the research.

00:16:41.290 --> 00:16:45.330
This one was quite easy for me

00:16:45.330 --> 00:16:48.490
because I let the people
speak for themselves.

00:16:48.490 --> 00:16:53.810
My only insertion of
myself was to edit

00:16:53.810 --> 00:16:58.840
because English was not the mother
tongue of many of these people.

00:16:58.840 --> 00:17:02.310
In fact, I probably
went through much more

00:17:02.310 --> 00:17:04.840
than 1,000 of these interviews.

00:17:04.840 --> 00:17:11.830 position:56%
And some of them the English was not
quite good enough even for editing.

00:17:11.830 --> 00:17:17.840
And so I chose those who would
show the range of atrocities.

00:17:17.840 --> 00:17:21.090
And it was rather like
being at an operation.

00:17:21.090 --> 00:17:25.100
I can stand blood, the slight
of it, I can watch these things

00:17:25.100 --> 00:17:27.100
on TV, it doesn't matter.

00:17:27.100 --> 00:17:30.310
Many people have said to
me how did you manage it?

00:17:30.310 --> 00:17:31.940
It's so frightening.

00:17:31.940 --> 00:17:35.650
But you can't write about the
Holocaust unless you describe how

00:17:35.650 --> 00:17:37.950
it was.

00:17:39.390 --> 00:17:42.470
&gt;&gt; Michlean Amir: So that leads
me to the next question which,

00:17:42.470 --> 00:17:44.770
again, you partially answered.

00:17:44.770 --> 00:17:50.480 position:56%
Was it emotionally difficult for you
to deal with these interviews day in

00:17:50.480 --> 00:17:56.120 position:56%
and day out, during the night when
you were reading them so thoroughly?

00:17:56.120 --> 00:18:01.090
Did it leave an effect on you the
next day or for a long period?

00:18:01.090 --> 00:18:02.670
&gt;&gt; Strangely it didn't.

00:18:02.670 --> 00:18:04.630
It should have but it didn't.

00:18:04.630 --> 00:18:05.950
I don't know why.

00:18:05.950 --> 00:18:10.830 position:56%
It was like when I visited Auschwitz
it was all scrubbed and clean.

00:18:10.830 --> 00:18:12.600
You couldn't smell it.

00:18:12.600 --> 00:18:18.620 position:56%
You couldn't see the people
suffering, skeletons walking around.

00:18:18.620 --> 00:18:20.920
It was all scrubbed and clean.

00:18:20.920 --> 00:18:23.230
And that's the effect
that this had on me.

00:18:23.230 --> 00:18:26.350
Many people express surprise.

00:18:26.350 --> 00:18:29.140
They said how did you
get through it?

00:18:29.140 --> 00:18:32.460
And I don't know, but
that's an individual thing.

00:18:32.460 --> 00:18:36.780 position:56%
It really didn't affect me, but know

00:18:36.780 --> 00:18:43.020
that if you read this book
you probably may not be able

00:18:43.020 --> 00:18:45.010
to finish it.

00:18:45.010 --> 00:18:52.170 position:56%
It's so horrific, and this is really
my reply to Dieudonne M'bala M'bala.

00:18:52.170 --> 00:18:55.020
They spoke and they answered him.

00:18:55.020 --> 00:19:00.890
