00:21:38.930 --> 00:21:43.280
To share with you a little bit
about a truly remarkable man

00:21:43.280 --> 00:21:48.250 position:56%
who survived -- can you hear me
okay, who survived really everything

00:21:48.250 --> 00:21:51.770
that the Nazis tried to do
the Jews with the exception

00:21:51.770 --> 00:21:54.690
of killing him which
they nearly did.

00:21:54.690 --> 00:21:57.400
So I'll try to answer some of the
questions and give you a little bit

00:21:57.400 --> 00:22:00.370
of background on Joe
and how I met him.

00:22:00.370 --> 00:22:04.910
Because Joe was raised in a
town called Radom, Poland.

00:22:04.910 --> 00:22:07.180
He was born in 1920.

00:22:07.180 --> 00:22:11.510
And when he was five years
old his father passed away,

00:22:11.510 --> 00:22:15.550
and life got very, very difficult
at that point for his family.

00:22:15.550 --> 00:22:18.910
His mother was widowed
raising five children.

00:22:18.910 --> 00:22:21.750
And all the kids were
just incredible kids.

00:22:21.750 --> 00:22:25.510
They all did everything they could
to help keep food on the table.

00:22:25.510 --> 00:22:29.590
When Joe was 12 years old he would
go from school to then working

00:22:29.590 --> 00:22:36.510
in a lumberyard to then after that
learning to make shoes at night.

00:22:36.510 --> 00:22:40.820
So they were just really
hardworking, loving, loving family.

00:22:40.820 --> 00:22:43.700
And when the Nazis
invaded, of course,

00:22:43.700 --> 00:22:45.620
they moved all the Jewish people.

00:22:45.620 --> 00:22:48.310
There were about, I've
heard estimates anywhere

00:22:48.310 --> 00:22:53.350
from 30,000 people moved into the
two ghetto areas of Radom, and Joe

00:22:53.350 --> 00:22:55.230
and his family were among them.

00:22:55.230 --> 00:22:57.630
I first met Joe in 2007.

00:22:57.630 --> 00:22:58.930
It was rather unusual.

00:22:58.930 --> 00:23:01.870
And I'm a very unlikely
person to be standing here.

00:23:01.870 --> 00:23:03.180
I'm not Jewish.

00:23:03.180 --> 00:23:04.940
I'm certainly not a
Holocaust scholar.

00:23:04.940 --> 00:23:06.620
If you told me a few years ago

00:23:06.620 --> 00:23:09.490
that I would be writing this story
I would have told you're crazy.

00:23:09.490 --> 00:23:14.310
That's not possible, certainly
not possible to be here.

00:23:14.310 --> 00:23:16.340
But I was working at a
retirement community in Ft.

00:23:16.340 --> 00:23:18.900
Collins, Colorado, and
Joe and his wife were two

00:23:18.900 --> 00:23:20.490
of our first residents
that moved in.

00:23:20.490 --> 00:23:26.560
And one of my co-workers told me
that Joe was a Holocaust survivor.

00:23:26.560 --> 00:23:29.260
And so I asked him -- a while
later I saw a little portion

00:23:29.260 --> 00:23:31.190
of his tattoo sticking
out from under his arm.

00:23:31.190 --> 00:23:34.900
He's got a tattoo that runs
the length of his forearm,

00:23:34.900 --> 00:23:36.540
and he keeps it covered always.

00:23:36.540 --> 00:23:38.290
But I saw a portion of it
and asked him about it,

00:23:38.290 --> 00:23:40.390
and he said it's from Auschwitz.

00:23:40.390 --> 00:23:43.480
And I said, Joe, our daughter
is majoring in history.

00:23:43.480 --> 00:23:46.860
Would it be okay if she interviewed
you for one of her classes.

00:23:46.860 --> 00:23:49.790
And Joe said, never.

00:23:49.790 --> 00:23:52.370
I will never talk about it.

00:23:52.370 --> 00:23:53.950
I didn't realize then that in

00:23:53.950 --> 00:23:57.730
over 70 years he had
never shared his story.

00:23:57.730 --> 00:24:00.380
Even his family knew
just bits and pieces.

00:24:00.380 --> 00:24:03.070
It was so incredibly
painful for him.

00:24:03.070 --> 00:24:05.550
That was in 2007.

00:24:05.550 --> 00:24:09.230
And then I moved with my husband
to Topeka, Kansas, but Joe

00:24:09.230 --> 00:24:10.530
and I remained really close.

00:24:10.530 --> 00:24:12.160
He's just a phenomenal man.

00:24:12.160 --> 00:24:16.890
He is the most joy filled
man I've ever known.

00:24:16.890 --> 00:24:18.190
And so we remained close.

00:24:18.190 --> 00:24:21.710
And I came back for a visit five
years after I first asked Joe

00:24:21.710 --> 00:24:25.820
if I could write -- or if my
daughter could interview him.

00:24:25.820 --> 00:24:27.170
And I was back for a visit.

00:24:27.170 --> 00:24:31.210
I ran into Joe, and literally
out of the blue he said, Nancy,

00:24:31.210 --> 00:24:33.870
I'd like to tell you my story.

00:24:33.870 --> 00:24:35.240
So I dropped everything.

00:24:35.240 --> 00:24:39.010
I went over to his house, and I
had no idea what it was I would be

00:24:39.010 --> 00:24:40.310
writing or hearing.

00:24:40.310 --> 00:24:44.240
I thought maybe it would be a
little keepsake for his family.

00:24:44.240 --> 00:24:46.220
But as soon as he started
talking I knew

00:24:46.220 --> 00:24:49.560
that this was a story the world
was going to want to hear.

00:24:49.560 --> 00:24:51.510
And it proved to be the case.

00:24:51.510 --> 00:24:53.500
I'm hearing from people
all over the world

00:24:53.500 --> 00:24:56.230
about the impact Joe's
story is having on them.

00:24:56.230 --> 00:25:01.240
People are telling me that if Joe
overcame everything that he did

00:25:01.240 --> 00:25:04.320
and did so with joy,
that they can deal

00:25:04.320 --> 00:25:05.790
with whatever they're dealing with.

00:25:05.790 --> 00:25:10.940
I heard from somebody from New
Zealand a couple weeks ago.

00:25:10.940 --> 00:25:14.740
A German police officer contacted
me a couple weeks ago and told me

00:25:14.740 --> 00:25:19.430
that because of Joe's story it's
changed his life, and he is vowing

00:25:19.430 --> 00:25:21.590
that it never happen again.

00:25:21.590 --> 00:25:23.540
And I love that.

00:25:23.540 --> 00:25:27.440
So as Joe began to talk
he told me that he wanted

00:25:27.440 --> 00:25:29.400
to get it all out once and for all.

00:25:29.400 --> 00:25:33.760
A to Z he told me, A to Z I'm
going to tell you everything.

00:25:33.760 --> 00:25:36.380
And he began with extraordinary
detail.

00:25:36.380 --> 00:25:40.870
Do you all remember the move The
Titanic, the fictional version?

00:25:40.870 --> 00:25:42.710 position:56%
And they asked the very elderly Rose

00:25:42.710 --> 00:25:46.660
at the very beginning tell
us anything you can remember.

00:25:46.660 --> 00:25:48.090
They don't think she'll
remember everything.

00:25:48.090 --> 00:25:52.370
And she says, I can still
smell the fresh paint.

00:25:52.370 --> 00:25:55.570
That was the detail that Joe
started telling me his story.

00:25:55.570 --> 00:25:57.270
He began like this.

00:25:57.270 --> 00:26:02.970 position:56%
It was four o'clock in the morning
and someone was pounding at my door.

00:26:02.970 --> 00:26:05.320
And I knew that someone pounding
at my door at four o'clock

00:26:05.320 --> 00:26:08.430
on the morning could only mean
trouble, and I didn't want trouble.

00:26:08.430 --> 00:26:12.440
We had had so much trouble
since the Nazis had invaded.

00:26:12.440 --> 00:26:13.740
I wanted to go back to bed.

00:26:13.740 --> 00:26:16.070
I wanted to pretend none
of it was happening.

00:26:16.070 --> 00:26:19.260
But as the oldest male in the
house I knew it was up to me now

00:26:19.260 --> 00:26:22.260
to handle what was on the
other side of that door.

00:26:22.260 --> 00:26:23.590
So I walked across the floor,

00:26:23.590 --> 00:26:26.270
and my hand was trembling
as I reached for it.

00:26:26.270 --> 00:26:29.730
And as I opened the door two
German soldiers were standing there

00:26:29.730 --> 00:26:33.790
with machine guns in hand
ordering me to come with them.

00:26:33.790 --> 00:26:36.130
And I told them but I
haven't done anything wrong.

00:26:36.130 --> 00:26:38.370
And they said you come with me.

00:26:38.370 --> 00:26:42.470
But I need to say goodbye
to my family.

00:26:42.470 --> 00:26:44.430
I need to change my clothes.

00:26:44.430 --> 00:26:46.540
They said you have
everything you need.

00:26:46.540 --> 00:26:51.300
And I looked down at my bare
feet, my sorts and my t-shirt,

00:26:51.300 --> 00:26:54.010
and I thought everything I need?

00:26:54.010 --> 00:26:57.330
And then they walked me outside
into the bitterly cold air,

00:26:57.330 --> 00:27:02.830
and they put me on an open
air truck with no protection

00:27:02.830 --> 00:27:05.330
where I would be huddled
with strangers.

00:27:05.330 --> 00:27:07.790
Several would die.

00:27:07.790 --> 00:27:11.950
And that's the detail that Joe
started telling me the story.

00:27:11.950 --> 00:27:14.480
And I was thinking, oh my
goodness, all I need to write

00:27:14.480 --> 00:27:16.680
down his words and,
Joe, here's your story.

00:27:16.680 --> 00:27:19.350
And then a really strange
thing happened.

00:27:19.350 --> 00:27:22.820
So we went from that
detail, and he said,

00:27:22.820 --> 00:27:25.970
and then they took me to Auschwitz.

00:27:25.970 --> 00:27:27.880
And while I was there I
worked in a coal mine.

00:27:27.880 --> 00:27:32.710
And then after that, after
the war I went to New York.

00:27:32.710 --> 00:27:35.900
And I jokingly said
I had A and I had Z

00:27:35.900 --> 00:27:37.570
which Joe was said he was
going to tell me A to Z,

00:27:37.570 --> 00:27:38.910
but I had nothing in between.

00:27:38.910 --> 00:27:40.840
And my next book is surely going

00:27:40.840 --> 00:27:43.810
to be called getting
to Z. Because I did.

00:27:43.810 --> 00:27:47.330
I spent the next almost
three years trying to figure

00:27:47.330 --> 00:27:49.520
out what happened in between.

00:27:49.520 --> 00:27:53.710
Because it was so incredibly
painful for Joe to share this.

00:27:53.710 --> 00:27:57.530
Seventy years he had tried
not to talk about it.

00:27:57.530 --> 00:28:02.100
Until he shared his story with me
he never told anyone what he did

00:28:02.100 --> 00:28:04.070
to survive at Auschwitz.

00:28:04.070 --> 00:28:10.330
His job was moving the bodies
of the dead from the gas chamber

00:28:10.330 --> 00:28:12.550
to the open pits, pushing them

00:28:12.550 --> 00:28:16.520
in a wooden handcart all the
while praying for the souls

00:28:16.520 --> 00:28:18.770
of those he pushed and praying

00:28:18.770 --> 00:28:23.560
that he wouldn't find his
family among those dead.

00:28:23.560 --> 00:28:27.750
And until he shared his story
with me he never told anyone,

00:28:27.750 --> 00:28:31.420
anyone that while at Auschwitz
he had been repeatedly

00:28:31.420 --> 00:28:34.590
sexually assaulted.

00:28:34.590 --> 00:28:38.540
Seventy plus years he kept that
hidden and tight and closed.

00:28:38.540 --> 00:28:41.410
And that to me is also one of
the miracles of this story.

00:28:41.410 --> 00:28:45.240
Joe was so incredibly worried about
his family learning about this.

00:28:45.240 --> 00:28:48.570
His grandkids, they're adults
now, but one of them said

00:28:48.570 --> 00:28:52.940
to him afterwards, grandpa,
I've never loved you more.

00:28:52.940 --> 00:28:56.500
And that was one of the greatest
blessings anyone could give

00:28:56.500 --> 00:28:58.820
to their grandfather,
someone who felt

00:28:58.820 --> 00:29:01.920
that if anyone knew
they may not love him.

00:29:01.920 --> 00:29:04.520
And it's such an important
lesson for all of us.

00:29:04.520 --> 00:29:06.180
So Joe was taken to Auschwitz.

00:29:06.180 --> 00:29:08.270
He arrived, and I thankfully
know this

00:29:08.270 --> 00:29:12.870
because of the Holocaust
Museum, April 30, 1942.

00:29:12.870 --> 00:29:17.150
He was at Auschwitz over two
years proper before being taken

00:29:17.150 --> 00:29:20.860
to several other camps:
Buchenwald, Ohrdruf and, finally,

00:29:20.860 --> 00:29:24.140
right before the end of
the war Theresienstadt.

00:29:24.140 --> 00:29:27.060
Just before the end of the war Joe

00:29:27.060 --> 00:29:31.050
and as the Soviet Army was
approaching that camp was in chaos.

00:29:31.050 --> 00:29:32.400
The Red Cross was coming in.

00:29:32.400 --> 00:29:34.190
The Soviets were advancing.

00:29:34.190 --> 00:29:36.000
And Joe looked out one day

00:29:36.000 --> 00:29:39.890
and he saw the Nazi guards
pulling civilian clothes

00:29:39.890 --> 00:29:41.520
over their uniforms.

00:29:41.520 --> 00:29:44.990
And Joe said to the man next
to him, what's going on?

00:29:44.990 --> 00:29:47.410
And they said it's over.

00:29:47.410 --> 00:29:49.380
They're going to hide.

00:29:49.380 --> 00:29:52.000
And suddenly there was
about two or three days

00:29:52.000 --> 00:29:54.430
that there was just
chaos in the camp.

00:29:54.430 --> 00:29:57.110
Eventually it would be
quarantined and shut down.

00:29:57.110 --> 00:29:59.360
But for a couple days
the gates were just open,

00:29:59.360 --> 00:30:02.510
and Joe said there was a sign
packed up saying you're free to go.

00:30:02.510 --> 00:30:05.350
And he was convinced
that if they walked

00:30:05.350 --> 00:30:08.130
through that gate he would be shot.

00:30:08.130 --> 00:30:11.120
But he said I was so
sick I didn't care.

00:30:11.120 --> 00:30:12.920
I was going to die anyway.

00:30:12.920 --> 00:30:17.830
And he simply with the help of
two buddies walked out to freedom.

00:30:17.830 --> 00:30:23.950
And so while Joe's story is a
tremendous story of heartache,

00:30:23.950 --> 00:30:25.890
he never knew when he
was taken from his home

00:30:25.890 --> 00:30:28.360
that he would never again see
another member of his family.

